try others. This naturally honors preferences without overcomplicating the algorithm.\n\n**Q4: How to represent time slots and track room availability?**\n\nOptions:\n- A) List of assignments per room — check conflicts by iterating existing assignments\n- B) Interval tree per room for efficient overlap detection\n- C) Simple sorted list of (start, end) per room\n\n→ Choosing: **Option A — List of assignments per room**\nReasoning: For typical scheduling problems, the number of events per room is small. A simple list with linear scan is sufficient and easy to implement correctly. No need for interval trees.\n\n**Q5: Cycle detection approach?**\n\nOptions:\n- A) DFS with coloring (white/gray/black) — standard textbook approach\n- B) Kahn's algorithm (BFS-based topological sort) — detect cycle when not all nodes are processed\n- C) Both — use DFS for detection with clear error, Kahn's for ordering\n\n→ Choosing: **Option A — DFS with coloring**\nReasoning: DFS with three-color marking (unvisited, in-progress, visited) naturally detects back edges (cycles) and produces a topological order in a single pass. Clean and well-understood.\n\n**Q6: How to maximize events scheduled (batch optimization)?**\n\nOptions:\n- A) Backtracking with \"try without\" — when an event can't be placed, try skipping it and continue; compare total assignments\n- B) Iterative deepening — try scheduling all N events, if fails try N-1 combinations, etc.\n- C) Greedy topological order with retry: schedule in topo order, track failures, retry failures in different room/time orders\n\n→ Choosing: **Option A — Backtracking with \"try without\"**\nReasoning: At each step in the topological order, try to place the event. If placement fails or leads to fewer total assignments, try skipping it. This naturally maximizes placed events. Need to bound search depth for performance.\n\nNow let me write the design document."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_inp